   =20
      Margining
   =20
 =20

One   point that I have made about the collapse of FTX is that, even if you=
 believe Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s story that FTX was undone by sloppy ac=
counting and carelessness rather than intentional fraud, that story is real=
ly bad, because FTX=C2=A0advertised=C2=A0itself specifically as a safe, car=
eful crypto exchange. If you attract customer money by saying that you have=
 a sophisticated automated margining system, and then you lose the customer=
s=E2=80=99 money, and then you say =E2=80=9Coh oops we forgot about margini=
ng,=E2=80=9D then that=E2=80=99s bad even if it=E2=80=99s true. Attracting =
customer money with lies and then losing it by accident is probably not=C2=
=A0quite=C2=A0as bad as attracting customer money with lies and then steali=
ng it, but both are very much on the =E2=80=9Cnot allowed=E2=80=9D side of =
the line.
On that note, we   talked yesterday about some reports that FTX was careles=
s about how it extended credit. Specifically,  the Financial Times reported=
 that, last year, Alameda Research, FTX=E2=80=99s affiliated trading firm, =
might have lost as much as a billion dollars due to a margining error at FT=
X. Some trader owned a lot of a strange illiquid token called MobileCoin, a=
nd the price of MobileCoin spiked, and the trader used that spike to try to=
 borrow a lot of money from FTX. Then the price of MobileCoin fell back dow=
n again, the trader=E2=80=99s position was worthless and FTX had to liquida=
te it. Rather than liquidating it at a loss and putting the exchange in dan=
ger, FTX sold it to Alameda, which took the loss. I suggested that this sto=
ry foreshadowed FTX=E2=80=99s collapse this year, which seems to have come =
about in part because FTX extended billions of dollars of credit=C2=A0to Al=
ameda, secured by Alameda=E2=80=99s giant stash of somewhat illiquid tokens=
 (FTT, Serum, Maps, etc.) that FTX had more or less invented.
I wrote yesterday that FTX was =E2=80=9Cjust going around lending billions =
of dollars against tokens that were not a thing,=E2=80=9D and asked why:

One possibility is, you know, motivated reasoning, fraud, etc.: FTX loaned =
billions of dollars of customer money to Alameda, secured by its own tokens=
, because that is a plausibly justifiable way to transfer money from FTX=E2=
=80=99s customers to its owners. I think there is something to this theory,=
 but the MobileCoin story suggests it=E2=80=99s not all that was going on.
Another possibility is, you know, naivety, dumbness, sloppiness, over-autom=
ation, etc.: FTX just thought =E2=80=9Cah well if a token=E2=80=99s price g=
oes up then it=E2=80=99s valuable and we can lend against it,=E2=80=9D so t=
hey did, without checking to see if the prices made sense or learning lesso=
ns when they didn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0

But here again I should point out that this is not what FTX=C2=A0said. A re=
ader pointed me to  a Twitter thread that Sam Bankman-Fried wrote in mid-Oc=
tober, not all that long before FTX=E2=80=99s collapse, about how FTX thoug=
ht about margining for illiquid tokens. He was writing about the Mango expl=
oit, which   we have also discussed, in which someone briefly pumped up the=
 price of a weird illiquid token and then used that inflated price to borro=
w a bunch of money from the=C2=A0decentralized finance exchange that issued=
 the token. Bankman-Fried:

So, obviously, ... MNGO isn't really worth $0.40; it's worth around $0.04. =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0But for a brief period, someone =E2=80=A6 bought enough MNGO=
 that it did trade for $0.40, and before people could get in to sell and re=
turn it to a more reasonable price, the risk engine had already allowed [th=
at person] to withdraw $100m from Mango Markets. =E2=80=A6
The oracle accurate reported the current price of MNGO. It's just that the =
'current price' wasn't really anything close to the 'fair price'. =E2=80=A6
What should you really do?
Well, let's look at what FTX does, and why *it* didn't have any risk engine=
 issues.

And then he describes FTX=E2=80=99s system for managing this risk. It inclu=
des bounds on price feeds, so that if a token moves by too much too quickly=
, you can=E2=80=99t borrow against the new price, because =E2=80=9Cif an as=
set's price moves 3x in 1 minute, it's decently likely to be bad data, or a=
 temporary wick, or something like that,=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Cif the asset=
's price stays there for 5 hours, that new price is likely the true economi=
c price.=E2=80=9D
  [1]
=C2=A0It also includes limits on margin for large positions:

The larger your position, the greater % margin we charge. For MNGO, the mar=
gin we charge is 0.00025 * sqrt(MNGO tokens). If you wanted to have a 500m =
MNGO position, FTX would have required, uh, 500%. (Bounded at 'fully funded=
'.) =E2=80=A6
The reason, basically, is that large positions--especially in illiquid toke=
ns--can have a lot of impact.
So we charge more % margin the greater your position is. =E2=80=A6
And some positions -- like the one in question -- are large and illiquid en=
ough that the risk engine forces you to fully collateralize a position.

And:

The Oracle [i.e. the price feed] tells you everything and nothing--the hist=
ory and current state of markets.
It's the risk engine's job to consume that information, and decide what pos=
itions are safe.
Sometimes it can't just regurgitate The Oracle. Sometimes it has to make up=
 its own damn mind.
Which doesn't mean that the risk engine needs to be manual.
You can create a set of rules for it so that it's conservative, and handles=
 apparent large moves gracefully.
That, in the end, is probably the most important thing we do at FTX.

A lot went wrong at FTX, and many details are still unclear, and I want to =
be careful about picking the most important thing. But if I had to choose, =
based on what I know now, I would say that the most important thing that we=
nt wrong at=C2=A0FTX is probably that it extended billions of dollars of cr=
edit to Alameda secured by collateral that was=C2=A0supposedly=C2=A0worth b=
illions of dollars, that a market price feed would tell you was worth billi=
ons of dollars, but that common sense would tell you was not.
We have talked about this problem=C2=A0here,   here and   here. The story s=
eems to be that Alameda ran into trouble on some trades this summer; it had=
 losses and its outside lenders were demanding their money back, so it borr=
owed the money=C2=A0from FTX. And it posted some FTX-affiliated tokens =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0particularly Serum and FTT =E2=80=94=C2=A0as collateral. Bloomb=
erg=E2=80=99s Zeke Faux   discussed this extension of credit in his intervi=
ew with Bankman-Fried:
It didn=E2=80=99t seem like a crisis, he says. It was a matter of extending=
 a bit more credit to a fund that already traded on margin and still had a =
pile of collateral worth way more than enough to cover the loan. (Although =
the pile of collateral was largely shitcoins.)
 Then Alameda defaulted on the loans, and FTX seized the tokens and tried t=
o sell them to a potential rescuer to bail out its customers; that did not =
go well. Bankman-Fried circulated a spreadsheet showing that FTX held billi=
ons of dollars of Serum and FTT tokens, measured by multiplying the current=
 market price of those tokens by the amount of them that FTX held. I wrote:

Something like 3% of the total value of Serum is held by the public and tra=
ding on exchanges. The other 97% is not. Something like two-thirds of that =
97% is held by FTX and Alameda. ...
One simple point=C2=A0here is that FTX=E2=80=99s Serum holdings =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0$2.2 billion last week, $5.4 billion before that =E2=80=94 could not =
have been sold for=C2=A0anything like=C2=A0$2.2 billion. FTX=E2=80=99s Seru=
m holdings were=C2=A0vastly=C2=A0larger than the entire circulating supply =
of Serum. If FTX had attempted to sell them into the market over the course=
 of a week or month or year, it would have swamped the market=C2=A0and cras=
hed the price. Perhaps it could have gotten a few hundred million dollars f=
or them. But I think a realistic valuation of that huge stash of Serum woul=
d be closer to zero.=C2=A0

That=E2=80=99s just, like, common sense, man. If you own 20 times the total=
 circulating supply of some token that you made up, you will not be able to=
 sell all of those tokens at the current market price, or half of the curre=
nt market price, or anything within shouting distance of the current market=
 price, or frankly any price. Your computer =E2=80=94=C2=A0your Excel sprea=
dsheet, anyway, where you multiply your token holdings by the market price =
=E2=80=94 might tell you that that stash of tokens is worth billions of dol=
lars, and that you can lend billions of real dollars secured by that stash.=
 But you=E2=80=99d know in your heart that your computer was wrong.
Bankman-Fried advertised that FTX=E2=80=99s computers were right! That FTX=
=E2=80=99s computers knew all this in their=C2=A0hearts, that =E2=80=9Cthe =
larger your position, the greater % margin we charge,=E2=80=9D that =E2=80=
=9Csome positions =E2=80=A6 are large and illiquid enough that the risk eng=
ine forces you to fully collateralize a position,=E2=80=9D that =E2=80=9Cit=
's the risk engine's job to consume that information, and decide what posit=
ions are safe,=E2=80=9D that =E2=80=9Cyou can create a set of rules for it =
so that it's conservative,=E2=80=9D that =E2=80=9Cthat, in the end, is prob=
ably the most important thing we do at FTX.=E2=80=9D It would have been! If=
 they had done it!

