<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off for the rest of the week, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Reg FD</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From first principles, you might imagine that =
the investor relations department at a big public company would want to giv=
e investors as much information as possible. Tell them what earnings will b=
e like next year, break down the drivers of those earnings, explain the ris=
ks, whatever seems helpful. And then if the investors have more detailed fo=
llow-up questions, you answer them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously there are limits. For one thing, you=
 would not want to give investors information that could hurt your business=
; you wouldn=E2=80=99t violate customer confidences or give away competitiv=
e information or whatever. For another thing, you want to be helpful but no=
t overwhelming; you might not disclose minute-by-minute revenue numbers bec=
ause that might annoy investors more than it helps them. But if anyone=C2=
=A0<em>asks=C2=A0</em>for more detail, sure, give it to them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Presumably this is not how every investor rela=
tions department thinks about things. For various reasons, some companies w=
ill have incentives to trick their investors. The main one is that some com=
panies will want to trick their investors into thinking that their stock is=
 worth more than it is, so that the investors will buy it (from the company=
, from its executives) for a lot of money; this seems bad but sort of under=
standable. (Some versions of it are fraud; others are, like, motivated reas=
oning and overconfident executives.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Other companies just won=E2=80=99t care about =
being helpful to investors; they will think thoughts along the lines of =E2=
=80=9Cwe want committed long-term investors who do not obsess over short-te=
rm quarterly results, so we will keep our guidance vague to weed out the sh=
ort-termists. Anyone who cares about next quarter=E2=80=99s earnings is not=
 an investor we want.=E2=80=9D (Or: =E2=80=9CIf we tell our investors every=
thing about what we=E2=80=99re doing this quarter to accomplish our long-te=
rm goals, they will pressure us to stop, because they care only about short=
-term results and won=E2=80=99t believe us about our long-term plans.=E2=80=
=9D) I find this position pretty annoying but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDYtMDcvY2Vvcy1zdGlsbC1kb24tdC1saWtlLXNob3=
J0LXRlcm1pc20_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIwNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1d=
G1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0=
dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc2e79753" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  it does seem to be popula=
r</a>.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still I presume that a lot of big normal compa=
nies will have investor relations departments whose basic goal is helping i=
nvestors understand the company, and whose basic instinct, when an investor=
 calls with a question about the company, is to try to answer it. Similarly=
, when a Wall Street=C2=A0<em>analyst=C2=A0</em>calls with a question about=
 the company, the company will try to answer it, because the analyst is in =
the business of writing reports explaining the company that are read by lot=
s of investors, so answering her questions is a good way to help investors =
understand the company better.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the US, there are two major=C2=A0<em>legal=
=C2=A0</em>constraints on this desire:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0My4xMDA/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBa407866c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Regulation FD</a> says that you cannot give o=
ne investor, or one analyst, =E2=80=9Cmaterial nonpublic information=E2=80=
=9D that you don=E2=80=99t disclose publicly. The intuition here is that yo=
u are not allowed to favor one investor =E2=80=94=C2=A0or one analyst, or o=
ne group of investors, or analysts generally =E2=80=94=C2=A0over the genera=
l public. Retail investors who own 100 shares and never call investor relat=
ions need to get the same information as Wall Street analysts whose job is =
to cover the company.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9C<a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDMvZ29sZG1h=
bi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9uLWdhbWVzdG9=
wLWtrcG9lNndzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdX=
RtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIwNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzd=
HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB71af9eed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Everything is securiti=
es fraud</a>=E2=80=9D says that, among other things, the more information y=
ou=C2=A0<em>publish</em>, the more likely you are to get sued if some of it=
 turns out to be wrong.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so companies mostly do not put out weekly =
public filings saying =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s how we currently think our qu=
arter is going, here=E2=80=99s our best guess about the quarterly financial=
 results, and here are some of the important drivers that we=E2=80=99re loo=
king at,=E2=80=9D because if those things turned out to be wrong or revised=
 someone would complain. And if you call up a company asking them for that =
information, they might=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to tell you, but due to Reg=
ulation FD they can=E2=80=99t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is a little hard to know what you should do=
, if you run investor relations at a big normal US public company. The roug=
h answer is something like =E2=80=9Cdisclose all the big important things p=
ublicly, being very careful to run them by lawyers and make sure they=E2=80=
=99re correct or at least appropriately caveated, and then if investors or =
analysts call you or come into meetings, tell them small things.=E2=80=9D T=
here is some category of stuff that is material enough that, if investors a=
sk you about it and you tell them, the investors appreciate it and understa=
nd the company better, but that is not so material that you have to disclos=
e it to everyone at the same time. This feels like a somewhat unsatisfying =
compromise. Some sorts of information will be in a gray area, where you mig=
ht think it=E2=80=99s okay to tell one investor, but later the US Securitie=
s and Exchange Commission decides that you should have told everyone.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But one further consideration here is that mee=
tings between corporate executives and investors or analysts are very very =
common, while Regulation FD enforcement actions are very very rare. So, uh,=
 not legal advice, but there=E2=80=99s a decent chance that if you tell inv=
estors information that you think is in the gray area, you won=E2=80=99t ge=
t in trouble for it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMDkvc2VjLWdvZXMtYWZ0ZXItYW5hbHlzdC1mb3Jlc2hhZG93aW5n=
P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1=
uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIwNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB50849503" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked last year</a> about a rare Reg=
ulation FD enforcement action against AT&amp;T Inc. Basically AT&amp;T lear=
ned that its smartphone sales were worse than it had expected, meaning that=
 its revenue would be worse than the market expected, so its investor relat=
ions employees called a bunch of Wall Street analysts to explain the situat=
ion so that the analysts could understand the company better. This worked, =
the analysts updated their estimates, and when the quarter ended AT&amp;T=
=E2=80=99s revenue was less of a surprise.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In some sense this is just good investor relat=
ions. In another sense, I suppose AT&amp;T could have put out a press relea=
se saying =E2=80=9Chey everyone our smartphone sales are coming in lower th=
an we expected, here=E2=80=99s how you should update your models,=E2=80=9D =
and that would have been=C2=A0<em>better=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0at least,=
 more equitable =E2=80=94=C2=A0investor relations. But there are risks ther=
e too, and in fact AT&amp;T=E2=80=99s chief financial officer spoke at a co=
nference and tried to gesture at that in a vague and heavily lawyered way:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During the CFO=E2=80=99s remarks at the March =
9 conference, which were webcast, the CFO referred back to his comments fro=
m AT&amp;T=E2=80=99s 4Q15 earnings release regarding the decline in wireles=
s equipment revenue and stated that he =E2=80=9Cwould not be surprised=E2=
=80=9D to see that trend continue.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The CFO gave no quantitative guidance about AT=
&amp;T=E2=80=99s wireless equipment revenue or any other metrics for 1Q16. =
Asked specifically by the conference host to do so, AT&amp;T=E2=80=99s CFO =
stated that he could =E2=80=9Conly talk about up through the fourth quarter=
=E2=80=9D and repeated the figures he relayed in January 2016 during AT&amp=
;T=E2=80=99s 4Q15 earnings call.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in more private settings, on calls to anal=
ysts, AT&amp;T could be more helpful, and it was.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC sued; AT&amp;T indignantly replied tha=
t it did not share any=C2=A0<em>material=C2=A0</em>nonpublic information wi=
th the analysts =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was in the gray area, but well on the rig=
ht side of the line =E2=80=94=C2=A0and this week <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9u=
ZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0yMTU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4b5f3b0e" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;"> they settled for a fine of $6.25 million</a>. The SEC says:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"The actions allegedly taken by AT=
&amp;T executives to avoid falling short of analysts=E2=80=99 projections a=
re precisely the type of conduct Regulation FD was designed to prevent," sa=
id Gurbir S. Grewal, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement.=
 "Compliance with Regulation FD ensures that issuers publicly disclose mate=
rial information to the entire market and not just to select analysts."</p>=
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It doesn=E2=80=99t really though. It ensures t=
hat issuers=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t </em>disclose material information to se=
lect analysts, but nothing about it guarantees that they <em>will=C2=A0</em=
>disclose it to the entire market. They can just keep quiet and have the ea=
rnings come as a surprise. I am not sure that that=E2=80=99s better.</p>
