<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Celsius</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you lend your crypto to a <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMjkvY3J5cHRvLWxvdmVzLWl0cy=
1zaGFkb3ctYmFua3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIwNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpb=
CZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMjA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25l=
eXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd9cddce1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  crypto shadow bank</a=
>, and the crypto shadow bank goes bankrupt, do you automatically get your =
money back? I=C2=A0kind of feel like that question answers itself? Like, th=
e whole point of bankruptcy is pretty much that a lot of people loaned mone=
y to a company, and it doesn=E2=80=99t have enough money to pay them back, =
so it goes bankrupt? Somebody is not getting all their money back? Like, sp=
ecifically, some=C2=A0<em>lenders=C2=A0</em>are not getting their money bac=
k? That=E2=80=99s what this all=C2=A0<em>is</em>?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People have weird intuitions about this. I thi=
nk that the two main, slightly different, intuitions are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If I have =E2=80=9Cdeposited=E2=80=9D=
 my crypto at a crypto shadow bank, then that crypto belongs to me, not the=
 shadow bank. I can take it out at any time. If the shadow bank is bankrupt=
, that=E2=80=99s its problem, not mine; my money is just supposed to be sit=
ting there in a box for me to take out whenever I want.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">If I have =E2=80=9Cdeposited=E2=80=9D my crypto at a =
crypto shadow bank, then it is a=C2=A0<em>bank</em>, and banks always give =
the money back.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Both of these intuitions are, I think,=C2=A0<e=
m>clearly=C2=A0</em>wrong. The first would make sense if the crypto shadow =
bank was not a bank, but just a custodian for your crypto, keeping it segre=
gated and leaving it alone. Some crypto exchanges work more or less like th=
is; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.27453=
2/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvY=
mFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0eC1oYWQtYS1kZWF0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVh=
bD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjA2MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U=
9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEyMDYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB28c73ad2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  we have talked about</a> one busines=
s model for a crypto exchange, which is to take customer crypto and just ke=
ep it in a box for the customers. (And make money on trading fees.) In that=
 business model, it would make sense for customers to assume that their cry=
pto belonged to them, that the exchange couldn=E2=80=99t use it, and that t=
hey=E2=80=99d be able to withdraw it with no trouble even if the exchange w=
ent bankrupt. In fact those assumptions are not particularly safe =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0Coinbase Global Inc., which more or less has this business model, <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTEvY29pbmJhc2Ut=
Y2VvLXNheXMtbm8tcmlzay1vZi1iYW5rcnVwdGN5LWFtaWQtYmxhY2stc3dhbi1ldmVudD9jbXB=
pZD1CQkQxMjA2MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2=
xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEyMDYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB53acef0d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  caused a stir</a> in May when it warned cus=
tomers that =E2=80=9Cbecause custodially held crypto assets may be consider=
ed to be the property of a bankruptcy estate, in the event of a bankruptcy,=
 the crypto assets we hold in custody on behalf of our customers could be s=
ubject to bankruptcy proceedings and such customers could be treated as our=
 general unsecured creditors=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but they are=C2=A0<em>=
reasonable</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand a crypto shadow bank that is=
 in the business of taking your crypto and paying you <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMjcvY2Vsc2l1cy1zLTE4LXlpZWxkcy1vbi=
1jcnlwdG8tYXJlLXRlbXB0aW5nLWFuZC1kcmF3aW5nLXNjcnV0aW55P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDYyM=
l9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90=
ZXJtPTIyMTIwNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZiN4ajR5N3Z6a2c_c3JlZj0xa0pWTnF=
uVQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB21579137" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  18% interest</a> simply ca=
n=E2=80=99t also be keeping your crypto in a box and doing nothing with it.=
 Where would it get the money to pay the interest?=C2=A0<em>Obviously=C2=A0=
</em>that crypto shadow bank is doing something with your crypto, not just =
keeping it in a box, so you can=E2=80=99t assume it=E2=80=99ll be in the bo=
x when things go wrong.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second intuition would make sense if the c=
rypto shadow bank was=C2=A0<em>actually a regular bank</em>. Banks certainl=
y don=E2=80=99t take depositors=E2=80=99 money and keep it in a box; a bank=
 uses its deposits to make loans to other customers,=C2=A0<em>It=E2=80=99s =
a Wonderful Life</em>, etc. If you put your money in a bank, the bank will =
use it, and it is certainly possible that the bank=C2=A0will do stupid thin=
gs with it and lose it. But if you are an ordinary retail depositor in the =
US, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. will make sure you get your money b=
ack anyway; those bank deposits are (up to a limit) more or less backed by =
the government. There is accompanying government regulation to try to minim=
ize the risk that the bank will do stupid things and lose the money, but fr=
om a depositor=E2=80=99s perspective that=E2=80=99s not the important thing=
; the important thing is the insurance.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel stupid even typing =E2=80=9Cof course c=
rypto shadow banks are not FDIC-insured.=E2=80=9D But I guess it=E2=80=99s =
worth saying. For one thing, people are so used to banks just working =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0paying interest and always having their money when they want it=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0that they intuitively assume that crypto shadow banks work =
the same way, without actually forming the question =E2=80=9Cis this crypto=
 shadow bank=C2=A0FDIC insured?=E2=80=9D in their minds. Crypto shadow bank=
s look bank-like, so if you are used to safe interest-paying bank accounts,=
 it=E2=80=99s easy to assume that your crypto is safe at a crypto shadow ba=
nk. Also some crypto shadow banks did, uh, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMjkvZmRpYy1zYXlzLWNyeXB0by1hc3NldHMtYXJlbi10L=
XByb3RlY3RlZC1hZnRlci12b3lhZ2VyLWNvbmZ1c2lvbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjA2MjJfTU9ORVlT=
VFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjE=
yMDYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB132a0738" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">  kind of suggest a little bit that they might be FDIC-insured</a>? No=
t a great look.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, no, an interest-paying crypto lending pla=
tform is not (1) a bankruptcy-remote box to hold your crypto for safekeepin=
g or (2) a bank. It=E2=80=99s just a company that borrows crypto from you a=
nd promises to pay you interest. If it loses the money, it will not be able=
 to pay you back, and it will go bankrupt, and you will have a claim for th=
e money in bankruptcy, and maybe you=E2=80=99ll get paid some percentage of=
 it, depending on how much of the money was lost and how much of what=E2=80=
=99s left has to be spent on legal bills.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDUvY2Vsc2l1cy1qdWRnZS10by1ydWxlLW9uLXdoZXRoZXItbGVuZGVyLW9=
3bnMtY3VzdG9tZXItY3J5cHRvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW=
09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIwNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ=
249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1b3acc85" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Anyway</a>:</=
p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A federal judge will soon decide whether depos=
itors at Celsius Network LLC gave up ownership of their cryptocurrencies in=
 exchange for interest payments, a key legal issue that could echo through =
other crypto bankruptcies.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Celsius has asked for US Bankruptcy Judge Mart=
in Glenn=E2=80=99s permission to sell $18 million of crypto on its balance =
sheet to keep paying its bills while it works on a way to repay creditors. =
But the coins in question came from Celsius users, who put the assets into =
interest-bearing accounts prior to the company=E2=80=99s Chapter 11 bankrup=
tcy in July.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That means Glenn must decide whether the crypt=
o in the company=E2=80=99s interest-bearing accounts belongs to Celsius or =
to its depositors. While hearing arguments in court Monday, Glenn said the =
issue is critical to the outcome of the bankruptcy -- it will help potentia=
l bidders, for example, understand what exactly they=E2=80=99re purchasing.=
 =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Advisers for Celsius argued that customers sig=
ned over ownership of coins placed in interest-bearing accounts when they a=
greed to company=E2=80=99s terms of service. But some creditors -- and a gr=
oup of US state attorneys general -- argued Monday that the terms of servic=
e were ambiguous, and pointed out that they changed over time.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYXNlcy5zdHJldHRvLmN=
vbS9wdWJsaWMveDE5MS8xMTc0OS9QTEVBRElOR1MvMTE3NDkxMTI5MjI4MDAwMDAwMDEzOC5wZG=
Y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBefcf84d6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">faintly insane briefing</a> fr=
om the state attorneys general:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Customers were told over and over again that t=
hey were loaning their assets to the Debtors and they could recall that loa=
n at any time they chose and receive them back. The use of the term =E2=80=
=9Cloan=E2=80=9D would certainly lead normal lay persons to assume they ret=
ained ownership of the crypto they entrusted to the Debtors. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[The] language is itself highly ambiguous, sta=
ting that =E2=80=9Cyou grant Celsius, . . . for the duration of the period =
during which the Eligible Digital Assets are loaned to us through your Cels=
ius Account, all right and title to such Digital Assets, including ownershi=
p rights.=E2=80=9D In other words, the very language upon which the Debtors=
 rely to show a transfer or ownership states, in the very same sentence, th=
at the assets are being loaned to Celsius. Clearly, such contradictions reb=
ut any claim that customers understood that they were giving away all right=
s to control their assets. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While the hodgepodge of contradictory and ever=
-changing language in the Terms of Use did remain constant in giving Celsiu=
s that power to sell, loan, and use crypto assets in its possession so that=
 it could implement the Earn program and pay rewards to its customers, that=
 power was given within the context of an overall agreement that guaranteed=
 customers the right to withdraw their assets without notice or conditions =
whenever they wished to do so and in the same form of cryptocurrency that t=
hey originally deposited.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes, no,=C2=A0 look, any time anyone lends mon=
ey to a company, the loan will also include a promise to=C2=A0<em>pay the m=
oney back</em>. That=E2=80=99s what a loan is! The problem is that, if the =
company goes bankrupt, it will not necessarily pay back its loans. That=E2=
=80=99s what bankruptcy is!</p>
