; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked yesterday</a> about some repor=
ts that FTX was careless about how it extended credit. Specifically, <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNWU5ZGM0MjQtYWVmNC00OTgxLWE0ZDctZTNjNDBlMWU2MDg=
1/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2db7d33c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the Financial Times reported<=
/a> that, last year, Alameda Research, FTX=E2=80=99s affiliated trading fir=
m, might have lost as much as a billion dollars due to a margining error at=
 FTX. Some trader owned a lot of a strange illiquid token called MobileCoin=
, and the price of MobileCoin spiked, and the trader used that spike to try=
 to borrow a lot of money from FTX. Then the price of MobileCoin fell back =
down again, the trader=E2=80=99s position was worthless and FTX had to liqu=
idate it. Rather than liquidating it at a loss and putting the exchange in =
danger, FTX sold it to Alameda, which took the loss. I suggested that this =
story foreshadowed FTX=E2=80=99s collapse this year, which seems to have co=
me about in part because FTX extended billions of dollars of credit=C2=A0<e=
m>to Alameda</em>, secured by Alameda=E2=80=99s giant stash of somewhat ill=
iquid tokens (FTT, Serum, Maps, etc.) that FTX had more or less invented.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I wrote yesterday that FTX was =E2=80=9Cjust g=
oing around lending billions of dollars against tokens that were not a thin=
g,=E2=80=9D and asked why:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One possibility is, you know, motivated reason=
ing, fraud, etc.: FTX loaned billions of dollars of customer money to Alame=
da, secured by its own tokens, because that is a plausibly justifiable way =
to transfer money from FTX=E2=80=99s customers to its owners. I think there=
 is something to this theory, but the MobileCoin story suggests it=E2=80=99=
s not all that was going on.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another possibility is, you know, naivety, dum=
bness, sloppiness, over-automation, etc.: FTX just thought =E2=80=9Cah well=
 if a token=E2=80=99s price goes up then it=E2=80=99s valuable and we can l=
end against it,=E2=80=9D so they did, without checking to see if the prices=
 made sense or learning lessons when they didn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here again I should point out that this is=
 not what FTX=C2=A0<em>said</em>. A reader pointed me to <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVy=
LmNvbS9TQkZfRlRYL3N0YXR1cy8xNTgwMTcwMjAzNjY0OTA0MTk1/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB0d196065" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> a Twitter thread</a> that Sam Bankman-Fried wrote in =
mid-October, not all that long before FTX=E2=80=99s collapse, about how FTX=
 thought about margining for illiquid tokens. He was writing about the Mang=
o exploit, which <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
9906050.274532/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjItMTAtMTIvZGVmaS1kaXNjb3ZlcnMtbmV3LW1hcmtldC1tYW5pcHVsYXRpb25zP2NtcGlkPUJ=
CRDEyMDYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dG=
VyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTIwNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB0159211e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">  we have also discussed</a>, in which someone bri=
efly pumped up the price of a weird illiquid token and then used that infla=
ted price to borrow a bunch of money from the=C2=A0decentralized finance ex=
change that issued the token. Bankman-Fried:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So, obviously, ... MNGO isn't really worth $0.=
40; it's worth around $0.04. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0But for a brief period, someone=
 =E2=80=A6 bought enough MNGO that it did trade for $0.40, and before peopl=
e could get in to sell and return it to a more reasonable price, the risk e=
ngine had already allowed [that person] to withdraw $100m from Mango Market=
s. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The oracle accurate reported the current price=
 of MNGO. It's just that the 'current price' wasn't really anything close t=
o the 'fair price'. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What should you really do?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, let's look at what FTX does, and why *it=
* didn't have any risk engine issues.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then he describes FTX=E2=80=99s system for=
 managing this risk. It includes bounds on price feeds, so that if a token =
moves by too much too quickly, you can=E2=80=99t borrow against the new pri=
ce, because =E2=80=9Cif an asset's price moves 3x in 1 minute, it's decentl=
y likely to be bad data, or a temporary wick, or something like that,=E2=80=
=9D but =E2=80=9Cif the asset's price stays there for 5 hours, that new pri=
ce is likely the true economic price.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It also includes limits on margin for large positions:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The larger your position, the greater % margin=
 we charge. For MNGO, the margin we charge is 0.00025 * sqrt(MNGO tokens). =
If you wanted to have a 500m MNGO position, FTX would have required, uh, 50=
0%. (Bounded at 'fully funded'.) =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The reason, basically, is that large positions=
--especially in illiquid tokens--can have a lot of impact.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So we charge more % margin the greater your po=
sition is. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And some positions -- like the one in question=
 -- are large and illiquid enough that the risk engine forces you to fully =
collateralize a position.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Oracle [i.e. the price feed] tells you eve=
rything and nothing--the history and current state of markets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It's the risk engine's job to consume that inf=
ormation, and decide what positions are safe.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes it can't just regurgitate The Oracle=
. Sometimes it has to make up its own damn mind.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which doesn't mean that the risk engine needs =
to be manual.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can create a set of rules for it so that i=
t's conservative, and handles apparent large moves gracefully.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That, in the end, is probably the most importa=
nt thing we do at FTX.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A lot went wrong at FTX, and many details are =
still unclear, and I want to be careful about picking the most important th=
ing. But if I had to choose, based on what I know now, I would say that the=
 most important thing that went wrong at=C2=A0FTX is probably that it exten=
ded billions of dollars of credit to Alameda secured by collateral that was=
=C2=A0<em>supposedly=C2=A0</em>worth billions of dollars, that a market pri=
ce feed would tell you was worth billions of dollars, but that common sense=
 would tell you was not.</p>
